fabulae is a noun becoming an adjective and, as Page says, equals ’ fabulari (compare virgo charta, γέρων λόγος, virgin effort). Horace says ‘all that is left for you is night, and the storied life of the dead, and the ghostly world’; he intentionally throws doubt on it all by making fabulae prepositive. Even such a world is doubtful (he cries); therefore eat, drink, and be merry.
